----------------------*-----------------------*----------------------------*------------------------
-> UNIQUE
UNIQUE is a constraint used to ensure that all values in a column (or group of columns) are different.
ðŸ‘‰ It prevents duplicate values in a column.
ðŸ”¹ Key Points
- A column with UNIQUE cannot have duplicate values.
- NULL values are allowed (but only one NULL per column).
- You can have multiple UNIQUE columns in a table.
- Different from PRIMARY KEY.
SYNTAX:- 
CREATE TABLE Students (
    Roll_No INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Email VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE,
    Phone VARCHAR(15));

-> CHECK
What is CHECK in MySQL?
The CHECK constraint is used to limit the values that can be stored in a column.
It ensures that data entered into a table satisfies a specific condition.
ðŸ‘‰ If the condition is false, MySQL rejects the data.
SYNTAX:-
CREATE TABLE table_name (
    column_name datatype,
    CHECK (condition));

-> NOT NULL
NOT NULL is a constraint that ensures a column cannot have empty (NULL) values.
It means every row must contain a value for that column.
-> Why use NOT NULL?
- To make sure important data is always present.
- To avoid missing or undefined values.
- Improves data integrity.
SYNTAX:-
CREATE TABLE Students (
    Roll_No INT NOT NULL,
    Name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    Marks INT,
    Result VARCHAR(10));

-> DEFAULT 
The DEFAULT constraint in MySQL is used to assign a default value to a column when no value is provided during an INSERT operation.
-> Why DEFAULT is used.
- Prevents NULL values.
- Automatically fills a column if the user doesnâ€™t give a value.
- Ensures consistent data.
-> Key Points
DEFAULT works when value is not provided.
DEFAULT does not apply if you explicitly insert NULL.
Can be used with NOT NULL.
SYNTAX:-
CREATE TABLE table_name (
    column_name datatype DEFAULT 'default_value');

-> FOREIGN KEY
A Foreign Key is a column (or group of columns) in one table that refers to the Primary Key of another table.
ðŸ‘‰ It ensures that the value entered must already exist in the referenced table.
ðŸ”¹ Why do we use a Foreign Key?
- To connect related tables.
- To prevent invalid data.
- To maintain referential integrity.

Parent Table (Referenced Table) SYNTAX:-
CREATE TABLE City (
    City_Id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    City_Name VARCHAR(50));

Child Table (Referencing Table) SYNTAX:-
CREATE TABLE Employees (
    ID INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Name VARCHAR(50),
    Salary INT,
    City_Id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (City_Id) REFERENCES City(City_Id));

ðŸ”¹ Here:
City_Id in Employees is a Foreign Key.
It references City_Id in City.

-> With ON DELETE / ON UPDATE
FOREIGN KEY (City_Id)
REFERENCES City(City_Id)
ON DELETE CASCADE
ON UPDATE CASCADE;

CASCADE â†’ Automatically updates/deletes related rows.
SET NULL â†’ Sets foreign key to NULL.
RESTRICT â†’ Prevents delete/update.





